This would be to provide a cleaner look to the first and last rows which often have lots of issues in them.

*Package*: com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira.boards.issueviews

*Usage Scenario*: Themethod DefaultBoardIsue.hasSubTasks and Issue.getSubTaskObjects is called from the Planning Board. This takes up a big part of the processor time.

*Current Implementation*: hasSubTasks determines if an issue has sub tasks by first retrieving the list of all sub tasks and then checking if the list is nonempty. In the call of getSubTasksObjects the list of all sub tasks must be retrieved again. 
public boolean hasSubtasks()
{
  return !isSubTask() && !issue.getSubTaskObjects().isEmpty();
}

*One Alternative Implementation*: Add a method getSubTasksObject to DefaultBoardIssue and cache the result. Collection<Issue> subTaskObjects = null;    
public boolean hasSubtasks()
{
  return !isSubTask() && !getSubTaskObjects().isEmpty();
}

public Collection<Issue> getSubTaskObjects() 
{    
  if (subTaskObjects == null) 
  {
     subTaskObjects = issue.getSubTaskObjects();
  }
    
    return subTaskObjects;
}   
To be able to profit from this improval change the call in the file issue.vm:
 <a href="javascript:Boards.retrieve('$boardIssue.key', 'subs');" title="$action.getText('gh.issue.subtooltip')">$boardIssue.subTaskObjects.size() $action.getText('gh.issue.sub')</a>

*Package*: com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.issue

*Usage Scenario*: Themethod getSortFields returns a set of all sortable fields. 

*Current Implementation*: For some methods the DefaultVersionManager has to iterate through all 20.000 versions and has to check for each version if a certain condition is fulfilled. Example:
public Set<IssueField> getSortFields(User user, ProjectConfiguration projectConfiguration)
{
  I18n2 i18n = i18nFactoryService.getI18n(user); 
  TreeSet<IssueField> sortFields = new TreeSet<IssueField>(new IssueFieldComparator(i18n));
}
For the internally use treeset an IssueFieldComparator is used. This comparator compares the translated field names and in case the field names are equal compares the field ids. The comparator turned out to be costly. Because the returned collection is a set, the order of the issues should not be of importance. 

*One Alternative Implementation*: Therefore a faster comparator could be used:public Set<IssueField> getSortFields(User user, ProjectConfiguration projectConfiguration)
{
  Comparator<IssueField> comparator = new Comparator<IssueField> () {
  public int compare(IssueField issueField, IssueField issueFieldToCompare) {
  if (issueField == null && issueFieldToCompare == null) {
   return 0;
  } else if (issueField == null) {
     return -1;
   } else if (issueFieldToCompare == null) {
            return 1;
   }
   return issueField.getId().compareTo(issueFieldToCompare.getId());
}
